1 A CONCURRENT RESOLUTION commemorating the 75th anniversary of the
2 Sport Fish Restoration Program as part of the American System of Conservation
3 Funding.
4 WHEREAS, more than a century ago, hunters and anglers were among the first
5 conservationists who realized America's natural resources were in peril and could not
6 sustain unregulated harvest and habitat destruction; and
7 WHEREAS, sportsmen and sportswomen took it upon themselves to support laws
8 that stopped the excessive harvest of fish and wildlife, established state agencies to
9 protect fish, wildlife, and their habitat, and advocated for special fishing and hunting
10 license fees to fund the new agencies' efforts to provide healthy natural resources for
11 future generations; and
12 WHEREAS, the primary authority to protect and manage fish within state waters
13 resides with state agencies; and
14 WHEREAS, realizing that license fees alone were insufficient to fund the
15 restoration and maintenance of healthy fish populations, anglers supported excise taxes
16 on fishing equipment to raise additional funds to support restoration and enhancement
17 efforts of the state agencies; and
18 WHEREAS, the Sport Fish Restoration Program, which is a vital part of
19 conservation funding in the United States, began 75 years ago with the passage of the
20 Federal Aid in Sport Fish Restoration Act in 1950; and
21 WHEREAS, the program was expanded in 1984 after the passage of the Wallop-
22 Breaux amendment to the Sport Fish Restoration Act; and
23 WHEREAS, a manufacturer's excise tax on fishing equipment, along with an excise
24 tax on motorboat and small engine fuels, is mostly distributed back to the states through
25 the United States Fish and Wildlife Service for fisheries conservation, management, and
26 angler and boater access; and
27 WHEREAS, this cooperative partnership between the sportfishing industry, anglers,
